@BhaviCodey Some options could be software engineering or computer science. That said robotics usually requires a number of different disciplines to bring the projects to life e.g. mech, electrical, controls, systems, or project engineering. Many ways and opportunities to contribute!

@bullah02 It really depends on what you hope to get out of your degree. Internships and coops can provide really great hands-on experience while in school. Also exposure to better understand what you're really interested in and an opportunity to make contacts.

Super cliche but we've only got one go at these lives of ours so if we have opportunities to help make each other's lives easier, better, more fulfilling, successful (however success looks for each of us)...it's a no brainer to me!
If you have the capacity to help others figure out or do what drives them, what inspires them, challenges them, gets them amped, then help. Help lift them up.
If you know what drives you, if you know what inspires you, if you know what challenges you, if you know what gets you amped, do those things.

Trust that the effort you're putting in to make paths easier for others will be realized. And just as important as working to create change: making time for activities that re-energize you so you can continue to play the long game.

I've received many questions recently regarding creating change and burnout. My take: creating change is a slow burn and you have to be in it for the long haul. Which means sometimes accepting you won't see the results of the change that you're working for.

@ibkjg A lot of people have not spent much time outdoors and just do not know (access to many outdoors spaces is often a privilege). Which is why education and sharing this kind if information is so important!
Treating places we are out exploring with respect will ensure that we all can continue visiting outdoor spaces and re-energizing in nature for a long time to come!

Dozens of people scrambling up all over the side of a cliff for example, instead of spending a few minutes searching for where a trail actually starts, causes damage (accelerating erosion) that takes a long time to repair.

This includes not leaving your pet's bagged business behind at the trailhead. And one often overlooked way to leave no trace is to stay on established trails if your destinations have them. They exist for a reason!!

If you are accessing outdoor spaces now more than ever, please please please practice leave no trace! It is super easy: treat where you're going like something you love dearly. Take out everything you pack in. Do not leave garbage behind.
